Abstract

The establishment of a sustainable lunar presence requires more than isolated engineering solutions; it demands a unified, adaptive, and epistemically aware infrastructure capable of operating under extreme physical uncertainty. Current approaches—primarily driven by organizations such as NASA and SpaceX—focus on component‑level optimization (landing systems, habitats, propulsion), yet lack a formal framework for global coordination under uncertainty. This work introduces the Multi‑PHT Epistemic Architecture (MPEA), a rigorous system‑level model for designing, controlling, and scaling lunar infrastructure supporting heavy vehicles such as Starship. The framework decomposes the environment into Physically Hazardous Territories (PHTs) and integrates multi‑physics modeling, distributed control, and epistemic state estimation. The central innovation, introduced here as Maakoul’s Truth‑Convergent Control Principle, reformulates infrastructure control as a joint minimization of physical risk and epistemic uncertainty. The key novelty lies in the coupled belief‑space control across multiple PHTs linked by physical fluxes—a scale at which existing belief‑space planning results do not directly apply. The thesis provides a fully self‑contained theoretical foundation, including multi‑mechanism plume‑surface interaction models, an epistemic Kalman filter for belief‑state estimation, existence and convergence theorems with careful treatment of the exploration‑exploitation trade‑off, spatial optimization with real lunar terrain data, and a phased construction methodology. All mathematical developments are presented with rigorous proofs where appropriate. No experimental validation is performed; the work is intended as a foundational seed for collaborative human‑AI expansion.

Keywords: Lunar infrastructure, Starship, epistemic uncertainty, belief‑space planning, truth‑convergent control, Maakoul principle, POMDP, plume–surface interaction, autonomous spaceports.

