6. Epistemic Modeling

The epistemic state of the infrastructure is represented by a joint belief b(X) over the hidden physical state. Due to the high dimensionality, we adopt a mean‑field approximation:

b(X) \approx \prod_{i=1}^n b_i(x_i),

where b_i is the marginal belief for PHT_i. This factorization is an approximation that enables tractable computation. The error introduced by this approximation is bounded by the strength of the physical couplings between zones. In the regime where the debris flux from PHT_1 to other zones is small or where the effects are localized, the approximation is tight. For stronger coupling, one could either (a) augment the factorization with pairwise corrections or (b) switch to a joint Gaussian representation; the latter would increase computational cost but is conceptually straightforward. In this thesis we adopt the mean‑field approximation for clarity and note that the framework can be extended.

6.1 Observation Models

Each PHT_i produces observations y_i from a sensor suite. Examples:

· PHT_1: accelerometer arrays (measure plume‑induced vibration), cameras (visual plume/regolith dynamics), LIDAR (surface deformation), thermal cameras (temperature).
· PHT_2: robotic rover cameras, contact sensors.
· PHT_3: radiation monitors, pressure sensors.

The observation likelihood for zone i is p(y_i | x_i, u_i), with x_i possibly only partially observed.

6.2 Epistemic Kalman Filter (EpiKF)

We adopt the Epistemic Kalman Filter (EpiKF) framework (Indelman et al., 2017) to explicitly separate aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty. In this approach, the state x_i is augmented with a set of unknown parameters \theta_i that govern the physics (e.g., erosion thresholds, bearing capacity, permeability). The augmented state is \xi_i = (x_i, \theta_i). The belief b_i(\xi_i) is a Gaussian distribution:

b_i(\xi_i) = \mathcal{N}\left(\begin{bmatrix} \hat{x}_i \\ \hat{\theta}_i \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} P_{xx} & P_{x\theta} \\ P_{\theta x} & P_{\theta\theta} \end{bmatrix}\right).

The aleatoric uncertainty is captured by the covariance of x_i given fixed \theta_i; the epistemic uncertainty is captured by the covariance of \theta_i (and the cross terms). As observations arrive, the EpiKF updates both the state estimate and the parameter covariances, reducing epistemic uncertainty.

The prediction step uses the physical model:

\xi_i(t+1) = g_i(\xi_i(t), u_i(t)) + \text{process noise},

where g_i includes the evolution of x_i (e.g., erosion dynamics) and assumes \theta_i is constant (or evolves slowly). The update step applies the Kalman equations with linearized observation models.

6.3 Convergence of Belief

A key property of the EpiKF is that under observability conditions, the epistemic uncertainty (covariance of \theta_i) converges to zero as informative observations accumulate. This provides a formal basis for truth convergence.

Lemma 1 (Epistemic Convergence) . If the system is identifiable and persistently excited, the EpiKF’s estimate \hat{\theta}_i converges to the true parameters \theta_i^* and P_{\theta\theta} \to 0 as the number of observations increases. (Proof follows from standard Kalman filter convergence results for linear systems with constant parameters (Jazwinski, 1970); for nonlinear systems, local convergence under sufficient excitation holds.)

