10. Related Work

This section situates MPEA within the existing literature.

10.1 Lunar Infrastructure and NASA Artemis

NASA’s Artemis Base Camp concept (NASA, 2020; Kessler et al., 2022) outlines a modular approach with functional zones (landing pads, habitats, ISRU). However, it does not formalize uncertainty management. Recent 2026 announcements (under Administrator Jared Isaacman) pivot to a sustained South Pole base with phased surface infrastructure, aligning with our three‑phase construction. MPEA extends this by integrating uncertainty into the control loop.

10.2 Plume–Surface Interaction

The PSI community has developed sophisticated CFD models (Metzger, 2024; Weaver et al., 2024; Korzun et al., 2024) that capture the four erosion mechanisms. Langley vacuum chamber campaigns (Korzun et al., 2024) and future flight instrumentation (SCALPSS) provide validation data. Our model synthesizes these into a simplified but physics‑based form suitable for online belief updates. The novelty is linking uncertainty over mechanism parameters to control actions.

10.3 Belief‑Space Planning and POMDPs

POMDPs have been applied to space robotics (Ong et al., 2024) for rover navigation, ISRU task allocation, and active SLAM. The Epistemic Kalman Filter (Indelman et al., 2017) and subsequent work on belief‑space planning under epistemic uncertainty explicitly separate aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty. MPEA adapts these techniques to infrastructure‑scale control, with multiple coupled zones, and introduces Maakoul’s Truth‑Convergent Control as a unifying principle.

10.4 Spatial Optimization for Lunar Bases

Recent studies have used CNN‑based site selection (Feng et al., 2024) and multi‑criteria optimization (Zhou et al., 2025) for lunar base layouts. MPEA adds the epistemic dimension, where the value of a location depends on how much uncertainty can be reduced there.

