Appendix C: Proof of Theorem 2 (Truth Convergence) – Detailed

Proof: Define the epistemic covariance matrix  \Sigma_{\theta}(t) = \mathbb{E}[(\theta - \hat{\theta}_t)(\theta - \hat{\theta}_t)^\top] . Under the EpiKF, \Sigma_{\theta}(t) evolves deterministically given the sequence of actions and observations. Let U(t) = \text{tr}(\Sigma_{\theta}(t)).

Consider the total expected Maakoul cost from time t onward:

V_t = \mathbb{E}\left[ \sum_{\tau=t}^\infty \gamma^{\tau-t} \sum_{i=1}^n c_i^{\text{Maakoul}}(\cdot) \right].

The cost includes the term \beta_i \mathbb{E}_{y}[H(b_i')], which is at least \beta_i \cdot \frac{1}{2} \log(2\pi e U(t)) (entropy lower bound for a Gaussian). Suppose there exists \epsilon > 0 such that U(t) > \epsilon for infinitely many t. For each such t, by (A2), there is an action u_t with expected information gain \Delta I_t \ge \delta(\epsilon) > 0. The expected reduction in future cost from taking that action is at least \beta_i \gamma \Delta I_t.

Now, consider an alternative policy that takes this informative action whenever U(t) > \epsilon, and otherwise follows the optimal policy. The cost difference between this policy and the optimal policy is at most C per step, but the informative action reduces the long‑term cost by at least \gamma \beta_i \delta(\epsilon) / (1-\gamma) over the infinite horizon. For \beta_i positive, the optimal policy cannot indefinitely avoid taking such actions; otherwise, its cost would be strictly higher than the alternative. Hence, U(t) must eventually drop below \epsilon. Since \epsilon is arbitrary, U(t) \to 0.

Convergence of the belief to the true state follows from identifiability and the fact that the EpiKF is a consistent estimator under persistent excitation (a consequence of (A2)). ∎

